    <div class="row">
      <div class="oc-information">
        <div class="oc-summary">
          <span class="mini-heading">What makes an ale, an ale?</span>
          <p class="mini-body">
          Ales use top fermenting yeasts and are fermented at warmer
          temperatures. In this way, the yeast remains active and the
          fermentation process is much shorter. Ales date back to pre-historic
          times and were often thick and gruel-like. Archaelogists determined
          that people usedto drink from communal bowls with straws.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="oc-characteristics">
          <span class="mini-heading">Characteristics</span>
          <ul class="mini-body characteristic-list">
            <li class="characteristic">More prominent malty and hoppy taste</li>
            <li class="characteristic">Traits are often dependent on where the style originated from.</li>
            <li class="characteristic">A fruity aroma and palette</li>
            <li class="characteristic">Ferment at warmer temperatures (55-70 F)</li>
